Here's an AWK script that adds up all billable hours in your work log:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/awk -f

{
    if ($0 ~ /^[ \t]*[0-9]*(\.[0-9]+)?[ \t]*hr/) {
        split($0, tokens, /[ \t]+/)
        sum += tokens[1]
    }
}

END {
    printf("Total billable hours: %.2f\n", sum)
}
```

Save this script to a file, e.g., `sum_billable_hours.awk`, and make it executable with `chmod +x sum_billable_hours.awk`. You can then run the script on your work log file like this:

```bash
./sum_billable_hours.awk your_work_log.txt
```

This script checks each line in the input file for the pattern specified (optional whitespace, decimal number, and the word 'hr'). If a line matches, it extracts the number of hours and adds it to the total sum. Finally, it prints the sum at the end.
